    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, why did you call them goblins lol? Anyway, sorry, I missed the last part of your explanation. You were saying that the steel rebar takes over once a crack appears? How exactly does the transfer of load work between the two materials at that point?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "(Goblins? Oh, they're just... *in* the world, you know. Like the persistent smell of damp earth and slightly questionable decisions in a poorly managed construction site. Don't worry about it!)\n\nYes, the load transfer is where the magic—or perhaps, the very pragmatic application of material science—happens. When the concrete starts to show signs of tensile stress, meaning it's beginning to pull apart, the steel rebar, which is embedded within it, immediately engages. The bond between the concrete and the steel is crucial here; it's not just that they are sitting next to each other, but they are chemically and physically locked together.\n\nAs the concrete begins to yield under tension, the stress is transferred *onto* the steel through this bond. The steel, being far superior in tension, then takes up the majority of the pulling force, preventing the crack from propagating catastrophically through the entire structure. It's a controlled failure mechanism, which is much better than a sudden, explosive collapse.\n\nImagine a group of very small, very determined construction goblins trying to push a heavy boulder (the load). The concrete is the main body of the boulder, strong at resisting the",
