    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The bond is a combination of both, but the surface texture of the rebar is absolutely critical, especially when you're dealing with the sheer, gritty reality of construction. The steel rebar isn't smooth; it has ridges, or deformations, which are deliberately added. These ribs act like tiny, interlocking hooks, much like how a very determined goblin might use a grappling hook to secure a particularly shiny piece of scrap metal to a wall.\n\nThis mechanical interlock is the primary way the load is transferred. When the concrete tries to pull away from the steel as it cracks, those ribs dig into the surrounding cement paste, physically resisting the separation. Chemical adhesion certainly plays a role too—the cement paste itself adheres to the steel surface—but if the ribs weren't there, the concrete would just slide right off the smooth steel under tension, and the whole system would fail prematurely.\n\nNow, back to the boulder analogy, because I feel I must finish that thought before the goblins start demanding tiny, poorly made tribute: The concrete is the main body of the boulder, strong at resisting being squished by the ground (compression). The steel rebar, with its textured surface, is like a network of tiny, tenacious goblin",
